<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow shows resilience after
fall led by bonds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US share prices lost ground yesterday after a sell-off in the US Treasury
market put investors on the defensive, but the blue chip indicator finished
well above the day's worst, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average of 30 blue chips was finally 7.88 off at
3,967.66, after fighting back from a 25-point deficit at midday. The
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 lost 1.29 at 480.71 and the Nasdaq composite
relinquished 1.78 at 797.79. New York SE volume, at 318.3m shares, was heavy
and falls outscored advances at the close by 1,180 to 919.
After a record-breaking session for most market measures and an 11-point
advance by the Dow the previous day, stocks were ripe for a setback. Bonds
provided the trigger, as growing speculation that the Federal Reserve would
soon tighten its accommodative monetary policy sent a shiver through the US
Treasury market. Prices across the yield curve slid, with the benchmark
30-year security down  11/32 to 99 1/4 in late trading.
The day's economic news was mixed, and somewhat inconclusive. The Labor
Department reported a 59,000 jump in weekly claims for unemployment benefit,
but the unfavourable trend was largely blamed on the cold weather and
disruption caused by the Los Angeles earthquake.
The Commerce Department said that December factory orders were up 1.2 per
cent. The figure was strong, but it fell just below the consensus forecast
of 1.4 per cent.
Most investors were focusing their attention on today's report on January
employment data, which may prove to be the last bit of evidence the Fed
requires before taking action.
Share prices of all three big US car makers rallied on news that the big
chill failed to stall January sales. General Motors, boasting a 14.8 per
cent increase in car sales, powered Dollars 1 1/2 ahead to Dollars 63. Ford,
with some impressive light truck figures, gained Dollars 1 5/8 at Dollars 69
3/8 . Chrysler kept pace with a Dollars 1 1/4 spurt to Dollars 62 1/2 .
Under the threat of higher short-term interest rates, many banking issues
were set back. JP Morgan, a Dow Industrial component, was Dollars 1 down at
Dollars 70 7/8 , Citicorp shed Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 42 1/2 and First
Chicago declined Dollars 1 to Dollars 48 1/4 .
Retailers also released data on January sales which generally held up well
under the adverse weather conditions. Wal-Mart rose Dollars  3/8 to Dollars
28 on the news and the Gap Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 41 5/8 . But Woolworth
fell Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 24 5/8 after warning of a fourth-quarter
earnings downturn.
Canada
A further mild retreat was seen in Toronto in record trading volume, leaving
the TSE 300 index 13.1 easier at 4,560.3 and declines outnumbering advances
by 426 to 370. Volume expanded to 106.4m shares.
Maclean Hunter, CDollars 1 5/8 higher at CDollars 17, and Rogers
Communications 'B', CDollars  3/4 lower at CDollars 20 5/8 , continued to be
the focus of much trading activity on Wednesday's news that Rogers intends
to make an offer for Maclean.
</TEXT>
