<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 94 / World Commodities Prices: Wool
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Wool prices in Australia and South Africa rose to new peak for this season
again this week. The WI market indicator finally ended at 546 cents a kg.
which compares with 522 a week before and makes an increase of 10% in two
weeks. The rise was concentrated in finer Merinos where twice as much is
being paid for some categories as applied in April,1993, the lowest point of
wool's recession. British wool prices also rose very sharply this week, with
increases of 10% to 15% typical. Pressure here exaggerates wool market
strength with offerings at Bradford auctions spasmodic and traders liable to
get oversold in times of recession, such as applied some months ago. At one
or two of the final Australian sales prices did tend to soften a little but
even if a quieter period is imminent the wool market's trend has been firmly
established.
