<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 94 / International Company News: Colgate advances 11% to Dollars
122m in fourth term
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Colgate-Palmolive, the US consumer products group, yesterday reported an 11
per cent increase in net income to Dollars 122.1m in the fourth quarter,
helped by its largest unit volume growth of the year.
Earnings per share rose by 18 per cent to 78 cents with fewer shares in
issue.
Mr Reuben Mark, chairman and chief executive, said every operating division
at home and overseas had turned in its best volume performance of the year.
Worldwide unit volume rose by 7 per cent and turn-over by 4 per cent to
Dollars 1.8bn.
The strongest growth came from Colgate's newer markets in Asia, Africa and
Latin America. Thailand, Malaysia, Hong Kong and Australia produced combined
volume growth of 17 per cent and Latin America produced volume growth of 11
per cent. Hill's Pet Nutrition increased volume by 9 per cent.
Colgate's mature markets did less well. In North America, volumes declined
by 1 per cent from a strong performance in the comparable quarter, and in
Europe volumes were only 1 per cent ahead - although this was the first
quarter in 1993 to show an increase.
For the full year, unit volume grew by 5 per cent and sales by 2 per cent to
Dollars 7.1bn. Excluding a charge of Dollars 358.2m for accounting changes,
net income advanced by 15 per cent to Dollars 548.1m and earnings per share
by 16 per cent to Dollars 3.38.
