<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 94 / International Company News: Vard shares tumble as AEA quits
cruise bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN FOSSLI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   OSLO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Vard, the loss-making Norwegian cruise ship and ferry operator,
tumbled yesterday as AEA Investors, a US investment company, withdrew its
Dollars 565m bid to acquire two of Vard's cruise lines.
Vard's shares fell 21 per cent to NKr51 in active trading on the Oslo
bourse. On Wednesday they were the second-most traded share when they rose
NKr4.50 to NKr64.50.
The collapse of the AEA deal is the second time Vard has failed to conclude
asset disposals in recent months. AEA and Vard had hoped to complete the
deal by this spring.
AEA said it had decided not to pursue the transaction having concluded that
its investment goals for the two cruise lines could not be achieved within
the financial framework proposed for the transaction.
Proceeds from the disposal would have enabled Vard to lift its position in
the mass cruise market by concentrating financial resources on Norwegian
Cruise Line, its remaining cruise business.
It had planned to strengthen, expand and modernise Norwegian Cruise Line as
well as reduce borrowings and strengthen the line's balance sheet.
Mr Terje Mikalsen, Vard's chairman, said a number of alternatives to the US
deal were being studied.
Analysts said the failure of the deal pushes fleet renewals far into the
future and raises questions over alternative strategies for Vard to
accomplish goals which could have only been made possible by the disposal.
They suggested AEA may have backed out of the deal because of reservations
about the potential of the high-risk cruise industry versus the cost of
participation and the return on investment.
Vard said bookings for the two cruise lines were stronger than in previous
years.
It forecast profits for both cruise lines in the current year.
</TEXT>
