<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 94 / Transatlantic to float shopping group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shares are to be offered in a new property company which will own seven
shopping centres, including the Lakeside complex in Thurrock, the largest in
southern England.
Capital Shopping Centres will become one of the seven largest listed
property companies on the London Stock Exchange. It will have gross assets
of Pounds 800m. Lakeside will account for half.
CSC is being created by Transatlantic Holdings, the life assurance and
property group controlled by Mr Donald Gordon, the South African financier.
He is best known for founding his country's largest insurance group, Liberty
Life, and buying into the UK's Sun Life and Sun Alliance.
Transatlantic, which is 54 per cent owned by Liberty Life and 19 per cent by
France's largest insurer UAP, will retain 75 per cent of the new company's
shares (issued at net asset value). It will also keep its non-retail
properties, worth Pounds 600m, and its half share of Sun Life and 3 per cent
stake in Sun Alliance.
The demerger will provide new funds for the retail operation. Transatlantic
hopes it will also lead to a more attractive valuation for the retail
properties.
Brokers expected significant interest in the issue. 'I think the market will
like the idea of having a large specialist retail property company,' said Mr
Chris Turner, of Barclays de Zoete Wedd. According to the brokerage, the
property sector is trading at a 19 per cent premium to its asset value, and
it is expected CSC will be priced above asset value.
Transatlantic will also raise an additional Pounds 200m from a convertible
bond issue. Mr Gordon, chairman, said this was to pay off floating-rate debt
and the Pounds 162m recently paid to increase the company's interest in the
Harlequin shopping centre in Watford.
Of the seven shopping centres to be owned by CSC, three have been built
since 1990. Mr Gordon said increasing consumer confidence meant potential
for a substantial increase in rental income.
Excluding the Harlequin centre, CSC's rental income is estimated at Pounds
28.4m for 1993, and the Harlequin would be expected to contribute at least
Pounds 10m in 1994.
The flotation, planned for April, is to be co-sponsored by Morgan Stanley
and Jardine Fleming.
</TEXT>
