<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 94 / Japan PM's tax plan delayed amid turmoil: Socialists force
rethink after threat to coalition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Japan's prime minister, Mr Morihiro Hosokawa, was forced to go back to the
drawing board early today on his sweeping plans for tax reform and a
Y15,100bn (Pounds 90bn) economic stimulus package.
A crisis meeting with his coalition partners to try to reach a compromise on
the tax plans broke up without agreement. Officials said discussions would
have to go back to 'square one' and a wholesale revision of the plans was
likely.
The fresh turmoil in Japanese politics began building up yesterday when the
Social Democratic party threatened to walk out of the seven-party ruling
coalition in protest at Mr Hosokawa's plan to raise sales tax.
Earlier a triumphant Mr Hosokawa had unveiled proposals for an income tax
cut worth Y18,000bn over the next three years, to be funded by a 7 per cent
'people's welfare tax' to replace the present 3 per cent sales tax in 1997.
The socialist SDP, elected on a promise not to raise sales tax, protested
that it had not been properly consulted.
Disquiet spread to other coalition members, including one of Mr Hosokawa's
closest allies, Mr Masayoshi Takemura, chief cabinet secretary, who also
threatened to resign if the SDP were not offered a satisfactory compromise.
Negotiators from the coalition parties met until late last night without
patching up their differences and failed again when talks resumed early
today.
The SDP has asked for the 7 per cent rate to be suspended - although it does
not take effect for three years - while a consultative body debates a new
rate. It also wants a promise to spend all the extra revenue on welfare,
initially rejected by Mr Hosokawa.
Political analysts have warned that fresh political turmoil might hamper Mr
Hosokawa's hopes of persuading the US of his government's determination to
stimulate economic demand. The Japanese prime minister is due to meet
President Bill Clinton in Washington next week for so-called trade framework
talks.
Details of the Y15,100bn package were released after a meeting between Mr
Hosokawa and Mr Yohei Kono, president of the opposition Liberal Democratic
party, which has started to co-operate with the coalition since last week's
compromise on political reform. But it cannot be adopted by cabinet and sent
to parliament until the row over tax is settled.
The package, slightly larger than expected, includes Y6,000bn of annual tax
cuts, mostly affecting income and residence tax. There is another Y9,100bn
of government spending and loans, which includes Y2,900bn of public works
and Y2,800bn of land purchases.
The tax cuts are worth 1.2 per cent of gross national product.
