<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 94 / Vietnam market opens for US as Clinton ends trade embargo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
President Bill Clinton last night announced the lifting of the US embargo on
trade with Vietnam, marking a big step towards normal relations between the
two countries.
The move opens the way for billions of dollars of US exports to the
burgeoning Vietnamese market.
Mr Clinton said Vietnam had provided 'significant and tangible results' in
the US's search to account for more than 2,000 servicemen listed as missing
in action (MIA) during the war. 'I have made the judgment that the best way
to ensure co-operation with Vietnam . . . is to end the embargo on trade,'
he said.
While the US also plans to set up a liaison office, Mr Clinton insisted that
full return to diplomatic relations would require further progress on the
MIA issue. He said he had no idea how big the trade opportunities might be
in Vietnam, as he had refused all briefings on this subject in order 'to
make sure that the trade question did not enter into this decision'.
But US businesses, 34 of which already have offices in Hanoi or Ho Chi Minh
City, have been keen to develop interests in Vietnam, as their French,
Japanese, South Korean and Australian competitors have moved into its
rapidly emerging economy.
Last night Vietnam's mission to the United Nations welcomed the decision,
saying it opened a new era. However, in the US, some veterans' groups,
former prisoners of war and conservative Republicans attacked it. Mr Robert
Dole, Senate minority leader, said the time for such a move had not yet
arrived.
Economic sanctions were begun against North Vietnam in 1964, shortly after
US military advisers became involved, and were extended to the whole country
after the Saigon fell in 1975.
Some US businessmen had feared a partial lifting of the embargo which could
have proved a severe competitive handicap. Companies such as Mobil, Chevron,
Boeing, Caterpillar and Digital have shown particular interest in Vietnam.
Over the last six years Vietnam has authorised 863 foreign ventures with
total approved capital of around Dollars 7.5bn (Pounds 5bn), and a state
committee said last week that it expected Dollars 14bn of foreign investment
in the next 10 years.
The issue of the MIAs is highly sensitive in the US.  Former president
George Bush was strongly criticised when he addressed MIA families in 1992
and Mr Clinton, who evaded military Vietnam service, was jeered during a
ceremony at Washington's war memorial.
America lays ghosts of its war in Vietnam, Page 5
