FT  04 FEB 94 / Observer: Commissar Chris
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The office of Chris Meyer, the no-nonsense press secretary charged with
polishing John Major's image, offers an insight - maybe a warning? - as to
how he plans to run the show.
Meyer has adorned his office with framed copies of Pravda, the once
all-powerful organ of the Soviet Communist party. Close inspection reveals
that the issues date not from post-democracy Russia, but instead from the
good old days, when anti-regime criticisms could merit a spell in the gulag.
Pravda's most important function then was to kid its readers that all was
well and the political leadership the best imaginable. Meyer's nostalgia may
be deeper than he thinks . . .
