FT  04 FEB 94 / Letters to the Editor: Pensions view challenged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr D J PARRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Commenting on Marks and Spencer's move into personal pensions, Lex
writes (February 2): 'The mass market may be better served by a standardised
M&amp;S financial product than the inappropriate personal pensions many have
thus far been sold.' Why? Is he implying that M&amp;S's in-house pension quality
will be as good as its knitwear? The M&amp;S unit trust performance figures
hardly support that idea.
Or is he implying that the strictly salaried salesforce will not use any of
the usual selling techniques? Does he seriously believe that the salesforce
will be free from all pressures of individual sales targets imposed by
management?
Your writers above all should know that independent financial advisers alone
can provide informed and impartial advice across the whole of the pensions
spectrum.
Moreover, we are required by law to assess the whole of the marketplace when
advising each individual. M&amp;S salesmen will, of course, be free from any
such commercially onerous duty.
What makes Lex think that M&amp;S financial products sold by its staff are, or
will be, any whit less 'inappropriate' than those sold by any other tied
salesforce?
D J Parry,
chairman,
Derek Parry,
Fortfield Chambers,
Sidmouth,
Devon EX10 8NY
