<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There are trios of programmes on both BBC2 and C4 tonight which, though not
compelling, are tempting. At 9.00 BBC2 shows the fifth episode in its re-run
of the first series of Red Dwarf, which satirises all those deep-space
movies from Star Wars to Alien. That is followed by Further Abroad, the last
in Jonathan Meades' hilarious series that folds architecture into social
observation. This week's subject is Belgium (9.30). Then comes a repeat of
Blackadder II in which Miranda Richardson gives an unforgettable portrayal
of Elizabeth I as a mischievous eight-year-old (10.00). Two repeats, but
good repeats, and one wholly original programme.
At 9.30 C4 shows the first episode in a new American comedy, Home
Improvement, which seems to have a doubtful basis for an entire series (a
DIY obsessive whose home 'improvements' always go wrong). That is followed
(10.00) by Roseanne, which makes some people laugh. Then (10.30) comes the
extraordinary series The Unpleasant World Of Penn &amp; Teller, also American,
which blows the gaff on conjuring.
</TEXT>
