<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 94 / Labour says tax debate gagged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER and GRAHAM BOWLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Labour party yesterday accused the government of 'gagging' debate on new
taxation measures, as the row over the parliamentary guillotine on the
finance bill continued.
Ms Harriet Harman, shadow chief secretary, said: 'The way the government has
tabled this debate shows that they want to stifle debate on key tax issues.'
Labour attacked the government for placing important issues at the end of
each day's procedures. This means they are unlikely to be discussed before
the guillotine falls.
The row arose after the government's decision to put a strict limit on the
time available for discussion of the finance bill. This is the first time
since 1974 - other than before an election - that a guillotine has been used
on the bill which implements the Budget.
Sir John Cope, the paymaster-general, said the government had allowed
'generous' time for debate of the bill.
</TEXT>
