<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 94 / Auditors propose change in liability
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A working group of the Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and
Wales has drafted proposals calling for the government to reform the law on
the liability of auditors.
Members of the group are calling for the removal of a legal provision which
prohibits auditors from limiting the amount for which they can be sued.
They are also recommending changes to the principle of joint and several
liability, which allows any successful plaintiff to pursue any one of
several defendants found to have acted wrongfully for the entire amount of a
judgment.
This can often mean accountants rather than directors or others being named
in a writ, since they are perceived to have the deepest pockets.
The proposals have to be ratified by the next institute council meeting in
March.
The arguments, which will be presented to the Department of Trade and
Industry, echo calls for reform made in lobbying efforts by the largest
eight accountancy firms.
The institute goes further than the firms, which decided not to call for
reform of joint and several liability, believing that a change was unlikely
to find favour with the public.
The group, chaired by Mr Graham Ward, a partner with Price Waterhouse, may
yet run into difficulties with smaller accountancy firms and accountants in
business, who believe the case for reform serves the interests of the
largest firms.
</TEXT>
