<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 94 / Promise on prison slopping out broken
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Howard, the home secretary, has gone back on a promise made three
years ago by Mr Kenneth Baker, one of his predecessors, to end slopping out
in prisons by the end of this year, David Owen writes.
In a Commons written answer, Mr Howard blamed the delay on the forecast
increase in the prison population. This has reduced the amount of prison
accommodation planned to be taken out of use for refurbishment during the
next two years, he said.
'The alternative would have been a return to the prolonged use of police
cells and an unacceptable level of overcrowding,' he added.
Mr Baker made the original promise in February 1991 when responding to Lord
Justice Woolf's report into serious riots at six prisons. In April 1990, the
then home secretary said the programme to give all prisoners access to
sanitation would cost Pounds 36m.
Mr Howard said the government's aim now was to complete the programme 'no
later than February 1996, the date recommended by Lord Woolf'.
</TEXT>
