<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 94 / Film institute's budgeting rapped
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MOTOKO RICH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The British Film Institute overspent by Pounds 108,000 at its London Film
Festival last year because of poor budgetary control, says a report released
by the National Audit Office today.
It warns that audiences are perilously low at the National Film Theatre and
the Museum of the Moving Image, both in London.
The report says that the institute's senior management agreed to unrealistic
budgets for the festival and officials were not monitored sufficiently.
Mr Wilf Stevenson, BFI director, said: 'I think the report is a little
unkind to us. We have to decide what films we are going to screen in advance
of knowing whether we are going to get audiences or not.
'The festival is by definition risky and experimental and it is in its
nature that you are bound to have uncertain spending patterns.'
He added: 'The expenditure overruns will not happen again because we have
put in better controls.'
The report pinpoints the National Film Theatre and Museum of the Moving
Image as vulnerable parts of the institute's operation. It warns that the
institute will have to take 'difficult decisions' if attendance levels at
the theatre and museum do not improve. Last year the National Film Theatre
filled 31,000 fewer seats than budgeted.
The report cites the recession, the theatre's South Bank location and
increasing competition from television as the reasons for the decline in
ticket sales.
Mr Stevenson said: 'We want to take account of the changes in viewer
behaviour and are making changes in our programming now. We will try to
offer what TV can't - what we call 'live cinema' - bringing in film-makers
to introduce their movies.'
Visitor figures for the Museum of the Moving Image have fallen from 536,000
in 1989-90 to 368,000 in 1992-93. Audience levels are now at about half the
level needed to break even. The audit office urged the institute to monitor
its marketing strategy closely.
Mr Stevenson said: 'A recent visitor survey said the Museum of the Moving
Image was the most popular attraction in London so we obviously have a good
product.'
</TEXT>
