<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 94 / DTI seeks to simplify arbitration law
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Department of Trade and Industry has published a draft bill to simplify
and streamline English arbitration law. The move is an attempt to stem the
loss of lucrative international arbitration from London to the US and the
Netherlands.
Mr Neil Hamilton, corporate affairs minister, said when announcing the
proposals that the move was part of the government's de-regulation
initiative.
He said the present arbitration law was difficult to follow because it was
spread across three acts of parliament and various pieces of case law. The
bill would pull the strands together and make English arbitration more
acceptable internationally, he said.
The bill is intended as a statement of the more important principles of
English law and is designed to be largely uncontroversial by introducing
reforms for which there is widespread support.
The draft was drawn up in the private sector before being taken over by the
Departmental Advisory Committee on Arbitration chaired by Lord Justice
Steyn. The document follows the structure of the Model Law on Commercial
Arbitration which was formulated by the United Nations Commission on
International Trade Law (Uncitral). This has been adopted by 16 countries.
It is hoped the bill will make English arbitration procedures both faster
and cheaper by simplifying English law and doing away with the need to adopt
many of the adversarial and oral procedures peculiar to common law
jurisdictions but unknown in half the industrialised world.
The bill contains a clause giving arbitrators freedom to determine their own
procedures and to decide whether to follow the English courts' technical
rules of evidence.
The DTI is allowing five months' consultation on the draft to obtain views
on a number of issues which remain controversial. The government
specifically wants to know whether the legislation should provide that an
arbitration clause is separable from the underlying contract and therefore
survives an invalid contract. It is also seeking views on the immunity of
arbitrators.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
