<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 94 / Romance added to firm's accounts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A small north London accountancy firm has decided to capitalise on the
consequences of the profession's unfortunate image as boring.
In what must be the most unusual diversification yet from the core work of
audit and tax advice, George &amp; Co, based in Enfield, has launched a dating
agency for accountants.
Just in time for Valentine's Day, it placed an advertisement this week
announcing its services in Pass, a magazine for trainee accountants.
'Prolink' is now taking calls from romance-seeking accountants and other
professionals seeking similar types for meals, films and discussions on
double-entry bookkeeping.
Mr Paul George, who dreamed up the idea, said there was a market for
accountants wanting to meet each other because of their reputation of being
boring, and to allow them to talk to each other about their work.
Dateline, the computer dating agency, said more than 10 per cent of all new
male applicants were accountants.
'Accountancy is one of the most difficult professions for people trying to
find dates,' said Ms Frances Pyne of Dateline.
She said this was because it was male-dominated and many accountants worked
alone or in small offices.
Young accountants were sceptical yesterday. 'I think we meet enough
accountants here already,' said Ms Natalie Marchant, who works for Price
Waterhouse.
'In principle there's nothing wrong with it,' she added hastily.
Mr Giles Davies, a colleague, said: 'It's a bit sad. I would only use it as
a joke. The assumptions behind it come right out of Monty Python.'
He added: 'Accountants do date a lot, but largely when they are training and
no-one else understands the pressures. It's a shame if you don't broaden
your horizons afterwards.'
But Prolink has already received nearly 50 inquiries from romance-seeking
accountants.
</TEXT>
