<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 94 / Pensions row faces second Commons probe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is to come under further pressure in the growing row over
personal pensions advice after a decision by a second body of MPs to
investigate the subject.
Mr Peter Lilley, the social security secretary, looks set to be dragged
directly into the firing line, with the social security committee expecting
to call him to answer questions before Easter.
The social security committee inquiry will begin as the government's
approach to financial regulation - particularly in the context of advice
offered to people to take out personal pensions - comes under scrutiny from
the Treasury and civil service committee of MPs.
The Treasury committee is to begin its investigation later this month by
taking evidence from two of the most vocal critics of the plan for
self-regulation through the Personal Investment Authority.
Its first witness is to be Mr Mick Newmarch, chief executive of Prudential,
the UK's largest life insurer, who has called for statutory regulation. The
views of the Consumers' Association will also be sought early on, as will
evidence from Mr Jim Stretton, deputy managing director of Standard Life,
who resigned from the PIA last month in protest that the planned composition
of its board membership did not amount to self-regulation.
Mr Anthony Nelson, the Treasury minister responsible for financial
regulation, is likely to come before the committee early in the summer.
In the case of both inquiries, MPs' interest has been intensified by a
series of revelations that have raised strong concerns about the quality of
advice on pension-related issues.
The Treasury committee announced its inquiry after the publication of a
study by accountants KPMG Peat Marwick for the Securities and Investments
Board, the City's chief watchdog. The study suggested that in nine out of 10
cases where someone transferring out of an occupational pension scheme was
sold a personal pension, the sale did not comply with regulators'
requirements.
The focus of the new inquiry - soon to be announced officially - will be on
advice given to people who transferred out of the state earnings related
pension scheme (Serps).
MPs on the social security committee argue that figures showing that a
considerable number of these people are now unemployed or on low incomes
give grounds for believing the advice they were offered was inadequate.
Statistics released by the Department of Social Security in December showed
a significant number of personal pension sales to people contracting out of
Serps involved people who could not benefit from tax incentives and so might
well be worse off as a result of contracting out.
</TEXT>
