<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 94 / Backbenchers may wreck shopping bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is seriously concerned that the shops bill, which liberalises
Sunday trading laws in England and Wales, may be sabotaged next week by an
alliance of Labour and Conservative MPs.
Supporters of Sunday shopping celebrated in December when MPs voted by a
majority of 75 in a free vote to allow all-day trading for small shops, and
up to six hours' opening for large stores.
The successful formula was put forward by an alliance of big stores as a
compromise between alternative proposals for full de-regulation or tight
controls.
The decision paved the way for ministers to fulfil a manifesto promise to
replace the widely ignored 1950 Shops Act.
However, the Home Office is worried that the Keep Sunday Special (KSS)
campaign, which sought tight Sunday-shopping regulation, may have found a
way to wreck the bill.
Ministers fear that die-hard Tory supporters of KSS will support a Labour
amendment guaranteeing double time to shop workers when the bill's
line-by-line committee stage debate resumes on Wednesday.
A Home Office official said: 'It is very close. We are not sure how many
backbench Conservatives will be willing to defy the government, but it could
be the best chance the KSS people have to wreck the bill.'
The government would reject such an amendment because it believes that other
groups of workers would seek similar statutory protection.
There is also concern about an alternative proposal from KSS restricting
Sunday opening to small shops, which would also have the effect of wrecking
the bill.
The government is not allowing a free vote on the amendments, in an attempt
to limit any Conservative rebellion.
But large-scale abstentions by Conservative MPs would be almost equally
dangerous because the amendments would have solid support from opposition
MPs, including those who voted for the six-hours option.
Even a narrow government majority could lead to serious problems when the
bill goes to the House of Lords later this year because peers are often more
willing to obstruct the government when its Commons majority is in doubt.
The Lords may also point to the absence of a specific government manifesto
commitment to the six-hours option to justify substantial amendments to the
bill.
The government will argue that any attempt to wreck the bill will reinstate
the existing unworkable law and could lead to widespread job losses.
But ministers have no prepared fall-back position in the event of defeat on
the double-time amendment.
Ironically, the big stores are less concerned than ministers because most
already pay between one and a half and two times normal wages to Sunday
staff.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
