<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 94 / Parents face fines for young offenders
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Parents could be fined up to Pounds 1,000 if their children do not comply
with court orders, Mr Michael Howard, the home secretary, proposed
yesterday.
Courts could force parents to ensure children under 18 turned up at
attendance centres or kept appointments with social workers or probation
officers.
'Parents cannot wash their hands of their children once they have committed
a crime,' the home secretary said. 'Teaching children the difference between
right and wrong is a process which must begin in the home and continue
throughout childhood.'
Courts can now impose a Pounds 1,000 fine on parents who refuse to be bound
over to ensure their children do not commit further crimes. Mr Howard
proposes that parents could be bound over to make sure the child not only
does not offend again, but completes the sentence already imposed.
</TEXT>
