<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 94 / Gummer to press ahead with review of councils
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The local government review in England will continue in spite of objections
from the High Court and backbench Conservative MPs, Mr John Gummer, the
environment secretary, said yesterday.
He will not appeal against last week's High Court ruling that the government
exceeded its powers in its guidance to the Local Government Commission that
the two-tier status quo should continue only in 'exceptional' circumstances.
But he reaffirmed his determination to establish all-purpose unitary
authorities in most of rural England. He said: 'The aim continues to be to
provide effective and convenient local government which takes account of
community identities. The government believes that unitary authorities will
often be the best way of achieving these objectives.'
Mr Gummer gave some comfort to backbench Conservatives who have threatened
to vote against proposals to abolish county councils. He added: 'There is no
national blueprint and the government does not rule out consideration of two
tiers in particular circumstances.'
Local authority reaction was divided. The Labour-controlled Association of
County Councils said the review, due by the end of this year, should be
postponed by at least three months while the commission adapted to its
changed guidance.
The cross-party Association of District Councils said the announcement kept
the review 'firmly on course for completion by the end of this year'.
Local authorities in England should be able to provide services in the
coming financial year at a cost their council-tax payers could afford, Mr
Gummer told the Commons last night. He confirmed that the councils would
receive Pounds 34.3bn in support from the national exchequer, an increase of
1.7 per cent over 1993-94.
</TEXT>
