<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 94 / TSB to pre-notify all fees
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TSB Group said yesterday that it intended to become the first bank to
pre-notify its personal customers of all charges on current accounts,
including those for returned cheques and letters written by managers.
The bank said it was introducing full pre-notification of charges
immediately. Along with National Westminster Bank, it now pre-notifies
customers of selected charges including overdraft interest payments and
fees.
Banks have been moving towards pre-notification of charges on monthly
statements, and the voluntary code of practice adhered to by all large banks
is expected to be revised shortly to include pre-notification.
Mr Ian Hall, TSB's marketing manager for cheque accounts, said that it had
been the first large high street bank to introduce partial pre-notification
in October 1992, but believed that was an inadequate service. 'We will now
be telling them (customers) about unexpected charges which they have no way
of calculating,' said Mr Hall.
Barclays has said it intends to introduce pre-notication, and Lloyds has
said that it will pre-notify charges this year.
