   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN, DUSSELDORF
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Plans for rebuilding Berlin as the fitting capital of a united Germany have
been sharply curtailed by the parliament's budget committee, Reuter reports
from Bonn. The committee agreed on Wednesday evening that all ministries
should be housed in existing buildings, either former east German ministries
or military headquarters left behind by departing Allied forces.
Only the new chancellery and government press office, due to be constructed
near the old Reichstag parliament building, were not mentioned in the
resolution. This implied they would be built, committee members said.
Union membership in Germany fell again last year, with members grouped under
the German federation of unions down by 6.3 per cent, to 10.3m, Reuter
reports from Dusseldorf.
