<HEADLINE>
FT  04 FEB 94 / PM concedes up to 3% rises in public sector: Concern over
job losses as 'new money' to finance pay increases is ruled out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN and DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday backed away from a confrontation with public sector
trade unions by accepting above-inflation pay rises of between 2.75 per cent
and 3 per cent for nearly 1.5m workers.
The settlement follows cabinet approval for reports from pay review bodies
covering teachers, senior civil servants, judges, the armed forces, nurses,
and doctors and dentists.
The review bodies' recommendations will be met in full from April, with the
exception of the armed forces, which will receive part of an average 3.6 per
cent increase from January. The awards compare with inflation of 1.9 per
cent.
The settlement was rushed through by the cabinet to clear the way for a
campaign to restore the government's battered authority before the local and
European elections in May and June. However, a political row was brewing
last night over the extent of job losses needed to finance the pay rises
without breaching a freeze on public sector pay bills announced in the
November Budget.
Mr John Major told MPs in a Commons written answer that there would be no
'new money' to finance the settlement, which will add nearly Pounds 1bn to
the government pay bill. He also ruled out a raid on the government's Pounds
3.5bn contingency reserve. Mr Gordon Brown, shadow chancellor, said the
settlement was a theoretical pay rise which would cost many workers their
jobs. Mr Alan Beith, Liberal Democrat treasury spokesman, said the planned
efficiency savings were 'code' for job losses.
Downing Street said departmental spending ministers had already identified
efficiency savings which would finance the bulk of the increases with
minimal job losses.
A senior official said opposition claims that the freeze on departmental
running costs would inevitably lead to job losses or cuts in services were
'arrant nonsense'.
'This decision has not been taken without the relevant ministers having an
extremely clear idea about where the savings are going to come from,' he
said.
However, the government's approach to public sector pay has clearly softened
since the Budget, when Mr Clarke insisted that efficiency savings should be
used to fund improved services as well as higher pay.
City analysts said it would be difficult to fund the rise in the pay bill
from productivity increases. Some suggested job cuts of 40,000 would be
needed to cover the review body rises. Union leaders were pleased that the
review bodies' recommendations had been broadly accepted. The bodies were
effectively suspended during the operation of the 1.5 per cent public sector
pay limit in 1993-94.
The unions were also pleased that pay rises will be close to those in the
private sector, where earnings are currently rising at about 3 per cent.
Mr Mick Graham, local government secretary of the GMB general union, said
that the 4m public sector workers not covered by review bodies would see 3
per cent as a 'benchmark'.
Mr David Hart, general secretary of the National Association of Head
Teachers, said the award was 'probably the best obtainable in the current
climate'.
The settlement means that public sector pay as a whole will lag behind the
private sector for the second year running after outstripping it in the two
previous years.
The detailed findings of the public sector pay review bodies include a move
towards performance only pay rises for senior civil servants and a further
move to hasten the introduction of local bargaining in the National Health
Service.
Review awards may cost 40,000 jobs, Page 9
Editorial Comment, Page 17
</TEXT>
