<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Rising bonds spark late
equity rally
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US stocks staged a late rally yesterday as a round of profit-taking petered
out amid rising bond prices, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average ended 11.53 ahead at 3,975.54, while the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 climbed 2.38 to 482.00, an all-time high. The American
SE composite added 1.90 at 487.89, its third straight record. The Nasdaq
composite gained 2.30 at 799.57. NYSE volume was 329m shares.
The day's economic reports elicited little reaction. The December index of
leading indicators and sales of existing homes were both strong, but the
market shrugged the reports off as old news.
With the US Treasury market unmoved by the release of the December data,
stocks were left with little direction. As a result, the Dow barometer
slipped into negative territory. But with bond prices showing steady
improvement in the afternoon, the blue chip index climbed back.
Oil shares were among the best performers. Texaco rose Dollars 1 1/4 to
Dollars 67 3/4 , Exxon Dollars 1 to Dollars 67 1/4 and Mobil Dollars 1 1/8
to Dollars 81 1/8 .
Cyclical issues were mixed, with Caterpillar down Dollars 1 to Dollars 104
5/8 and Cummins Engine off Dollars 1 at Dollars 53 3/4 , but Union Carbide
Dollars 1 3/8 ahead at Dollars 26 and General Electric up Dollars 2 1/8 at
Dollars 109.
The blue chip Dow index was held back from a run into record territory by
Sears Roebuck. The retailer fell Dollars 2 1/2 to Dollars 51 1/4 when
Prudential Securities cut its rating on the stock.
The struggle to take over Paramount Communications provided a focal point
for the morning's activity, after Viacom and QVC both sweetened their bids
for the company moments before Tuesday's deadline.
With the winner still uncertain, Viacom's 'B' shares slipped Dollars 1/2 to
Dollars 33 1/2 . QVC gained Dollars 2 at Dollars 46 3/4 as investors bet
that the cable network would lose the battle. The target company fell
Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 78 after warning that it expected to post a net
loss of 29 to 33 cents a share in the three months to end-January.
Sprint, the long-distance telephone concern, advanced Dollars 1 5/8 to
Dollars 37 1/8 on its announcement of record revenues and income in the
fourth quarter.
On the Nasdaq, Amgen retreated Dollars 3 to Dollars 44 on a downgrading by
SG Warburg. Concern over the sales of its Neupogen treatment has depressed
the stock of late.
Canada
Toronto ended a five-day winning streak, slipping back in extremely heavy
trading. The TSE 300 index ended 17.8 off at 4,573.4, while falls led rises
by 439 to 393 after volume of 96m shares valued at CDollars 1.279bn. Golds
and banking shed 1.83 and 1.30 per cent respectively.
The communications and media sub-group rose 2.06 per cent. The increase
followed Maclean Hunter's announcement of a proposed takeover bid for it by
Rogers Communications. Maclean jumped CDollars 1 5/8 to CDollars 15 3/8 and
Rogers 'B' dipped CDollars  7/8 to CDollars 21 3/8.
</TEXT>
