FT  03 FEB 94 / International Company News: Sears Canada swings back to the
black
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Canada's biggest department store retailer, Sears Canada, turned round in
the final quarter of 1993, putting the chain into the black for the first
time in two years.
The company, which operates 110 stores and about 1,500 catalogue businesses,
has undergone a substantial restructuring.
Net profit in the December quarter was CDollars 50.6m (USDollars 38.1m), or
53 cents a share, against a loss of CDollars 3.7m, or 4 cents, a year
earlier, on revenues little changed at CDollars 1.3bn. Profit for all 1993
was CDollars 4.4m, or 5 cents, against a loss of CDollars 90.9m, or CDollars
1.44, on revenues of almost CDollars 4bn, little changed.
