<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 94 / Siebe calls end to 'dinosaur war'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Peace has broken out in the 'dinosaur war' - a bitter and abusive struggle
for market share between two of the world's leading suppliers of advanced
process control systems.
A settlement has been agreed between Honeywell, the US giant which dominates
the world market, and Foxboro, the Massachusetts-based subsidiary of Siebe,
the UK engineering group.
Under the agreement, Foxboro will tell its sales force to stop a 'dinosaur
advertising campaign' and related promotional activities, which - without
naming Honeywell - claimed that competitive products were obsolete.
Honeywell will tell its sales force not to distribute to customers sales
training material directed at Foxboro and not to make statements which
criticise its competitor.
An agreed statement said: 'Both parties intend to vigorously compete in
future by concentrating on promoting the advantages of their own companies
and products.'
If hostilities have indeed ceased, it will be a novel working situation for
sales staff and executives in both groups. When the UK group bought Foxboro
for Dollars 656m (Pounds 437m) in 1990, the then chairman and chief
executive of the US company was quoted as saying Siebe intended to 'bury'
Honeywell.
Mr Barrie Stephens, the chairman and forceful founder of the modern Siebe,
once startled a meeting of analysts by saying: 'I see the chairman of
Honeywell mentioned us twice in his last statement. We must be getting the
son of a bitch worried.'
Mr Allen Yurko, who took over as chief executive from Mr Stephens at the
beginning of the year, said he was very pleased with the settlement of the
legal action, which was launched by Foxboro. 'It resolves the issue and gets
us all back to the promotion of our own products.'
Competition is fiercest at the top end of the process control market, where
automation systems are used to control everything from oil refineries to
food processing plants.
Foxboro yesterday said it had won a batch of international contracts worth
more than Pounds 36m in recent months. Four of the largest contracts - each
worth more than Pounds 5m - are for the group's Intelligent/Automation (I/A)
Series, which Mr Yurko said was a technological leader. One of the largest
orders is from the Chiyoda Corporation of Japan, for a liquefied natural gas
plant in the Gulf state of Qatar.
Another is the modernisation of the Kuwait National Petroleum Company's Mina
Al Ahmadi refinery, the first major modernisation project undertaken by KNPC
since the Gulf War.
Mr Yurko said this confirmed there was a vibrant market for process control
updates in the Middle East. Other large orders were in Thailand and
Argentina.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Honeywell Inc.
    Foxboro Co Inc.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P3669 Communications Equipment, NEC.
    P3812 Search and Navigation Equipment.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>MGMT  Management &amp; Marketing.
