<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 94 / Heseltine pressed over Post Office
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Members of the Commons trade and industry committee yesterday criticised Mr
Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, for failing to give the
Post Office more commercial freedom.
Mr Richard Caborn, the Labour chairman, said: 'To dismiss giving the Post
Office more commercialism is disgraceful. The committee believes the status
quo is the worst possible option.'
Mr Heseltine gave evidence to the committee on Tuesday and the MPs are
determined to keep up the pressure on the DTI to speed up its review into
the future of the corporation.
Mr Heseltine told the committee he favoured privatisation of the Royal Mail
letters division but had been prevented from changing its ownership because
of 'political considerations'. He said more commercialisation within the
public sector was proving very difficult to achieve.
A senior Conservative member of the committee said privately that he backed
the call for greater freedom within the public sector.
Mr Malcolm Bruce, Liberal Democrat trade and industry spokesman, accused the
DTI of 'damaging the business of the Post Office' by failing to make a
decision. He has written to Mr Heseltine urging him to give an early answer
on the future of the corporation and to recognise its need to work with the
private sector.
Mr Bill Cockburn, Post Office chief executive, agreed with Mr Heseltine's
view that there was a strong economic case for privatising the Royal Mail
while leaving Post Office shops in the public sector.
The Post Office revealed that the increase in the amount it has to give the
government was mainly responsible for November's price increase.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
