<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 94 / Smithfield demands rejected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Corporation of London yesterday rejected demands for extra subsidies for
Smithfield meat market and announced that it would end negotiations with the
Smithfield Market Tenants' Association.
Smithfield and the corporation are in dispute over how the Pounds 60m
refurbishment of the market to meet European Union regulations should be
funded. Two members of the association have been elected to the
corporation's general council as part of its campaign against rent rises of
between 85 per cent and 135 per cent.
Mr Jack Neary, the corporation's central markets chairman, said: 'The
tenants' negotiators are seeking to have new premises provided by the
corporation at what seems to be little or no increase in cost to them.
'Recent discussions illustrate . . . that they are not prepared to accept
the realities of the situation, so no meaningful progress is possible.'
</TEXT>
