FT  03 FEB 94 / Labour refuses to debate Clause 4
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Labour Leadership yesterday dismissed Mr Neil Kinnock's call to drop
Clause 4 of its constitution as 'a massive distraction' from winning
elections, Roland Rudd writes.
The former Labour leader said he wanted the controversial clause -
committing the party to nationalisation - to be replaced. He argued that the
clause was not an adequate definition of modern socialism, which should be
concerned with individual liberty.
The Labour leadership said it had no intention of 'opening up another flank'
in the run-up to the local and European elections by taking part in a debate
which could prove distracting.
