<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 94 / Move on account loopholes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Accountants in business will be obliged under guidelines issued yesterday to
discourage fellow directors and officers from using 'creative accounting'
loopholes.
The onus will be on all members of any of the six leading professional
accountancy bodies in the UK to pass on the pronouncements from the
urgent-issues taskforce of the Accounting Standards Board.
The details are included as part of the foreword to urgent-issues taskforce
abstracts, issued by the board yesterday.
The taskforce is designed to prevent what Mr David Tweedie, board chairman,
calls 'the creeping crumple' - the process by which auditors were in the
past coerced into allowing clients to exploit creative accounting loopholes
because other firms of auditors had already approved the accounting
technique in another company.
The taskforce was set up as part of the new machinery for financial
reporting created under the 1989 Companies Act.
The foreword states that the Accounting Standards Board has the right to
reject any statement issued by the taskforce if it contradicts legislation
or the direction of financial reporting being taken by the board.
Foreword to UITF abstracts. ASB publications, PO Box 620, Central Milton
Keynes, MK9 2JX. Pounds 5.
</TEXT>
