<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 94 / Tenant safeguard measures urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tenants should have greater protection from eviction, the Law Commission
said yesterday. The proposal was among a number of suggestions for reform of
the law on termination on tenancies put forward by the government's law
reform body.
The commission said the 'complex, confused and defective' law needed urgent
reform. Parts of the law date back 150 years.
It recommends that a landlord should not be allowed to take a property back
without a court order or the tenant's agreement if the tenant is in default
for non-payment of rent or for breach of some other obligation in a lease.
Landlords have the right in some cases now simply to repossess the property
 -a right of 'peaceable re-entry' described by a law lord recently as
'dangerous'.
The commission also proposes that courts should be able to give tenants the
chance to save their tenancies by taking appropriate remedial action, and
that there should be a single set of rules governing the landlord's right of
forfeiture. At the moment there are different rules depending on whether
forfeiture is as a result of non-payment of rent or other defaults.
The commission recommends that a landlord should be required to give
preliminary notice of forfeiture only when a tenant has failed to comply
with an obligation to repair the property. Landlords would lose the right of
forfeiture only if, knowing the facts, they behaved in a way which would
lead a reasonable tenant to believe they did not intend to end the lease. At
present a landlord can lose the right by merely sending a rent demand.
These reforms, which would apply to all types of leases were first put
forward by the commission in 1985. They have been re-submitted together with
a draft bill.
Termination of Tenancies Bill, Law Com No 221, HC 135. HMSO. Pounds 15.10.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6512 Nonresidential Buildings Operators.
    P8111 Legal Services.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
