<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 94 / Traffic levels 'pose benzene pollution threat'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Rising traffic levels threaten to lead to harmful levels of benzene in the
air, a government panel of scientists warned yesterday.
Fitting catalytic converters to more cars and improving public transport
would help, the scientists said.
The report by the expert panel on air quality standards, set up two years
ago after the 1990 white paper on the environment, recommends that levels of
benzene in the air should not exceed 5ppb - parts per billion - calculated
as a running annual average.
It also recommends that the standard eventually be reduced to 1ppb and that
the government set a target date for achieving this.
Professor Anthony Seaton of Aberdeen University, chairman of the panel, said
that the 5ppb standard 'would broadly be able to be met at present', but
1ppb would be more difficult.
Mr Robert Atkins, environment minister, said the government would soon
publish a consultation paper on how the standards should be applied.
Evidence indicating that benzene causes a form of leukaemia has been
accumulating for some 15 years. The World Health Organisation has not
recommended standards, saying there is no completely 'safe' level for such
chemicals.
However, the panel said yesterday that at the levels it has recommended,
'the risks are exceedingly small and unlikely to be detectable by any
practicable method'.
Smoking 20 cigarettes a day more than doubles the exposure to benzene for
someone living in a town.
Nearly 80 per cent of benzene in the air comes from petrol cars. Since the
start of last year, all new cars have been fitted with catalytic converters
which reduce these emissions almost entirely.
Diesel engines emit only 9 per cent of airborne benzene, but they also emit
harmful carbon particles, as a government report last week warned. Petrol
pumps emit a small amount, and food and water also contain traces, the panel
said.
The panel will publish further recommendations on levels of other
pollutants, including carbon monoxide, sulphur dioxide, nitrogen oxides,
ozone and carbon particles.
The Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders yesterday attacked the
government's promotion of unleaded fuel, which contains much more benzene
than leaded fuel. Cars with catalytic converters need unleaded fuel but emit
little benzene; cars which run on unleaded but have no converters emit high
levels.
Benzene, Expert Panel on Air Quality Standards. HMSO. Pounds 5.95.
</TEXT>
<XX>
