<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 94 / Consumer credit shows 36 per cent increase: Confidence
stimulated by lower interest rates and receding fear of unemployment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Consumer credit in December was 36 per cent higher than in December 1992,
the Finance &amp; Leasing Association said yesterday. The figures indicate that
consumer confidence has revived as interest rates and the fear of
unemployment have declined.
The association, which represents companies providing consumer credit,
business finance and leasing, and motor finance, said it was surprised by
the weak trend in official retail sales figures for December. Those showed a
seasonally adjusted fall of 0.2 per cent from November and an annual rise of
just 4 per cent.
However, the credit figures may indicate that consumers are increasingly
turning to store cards or hire purchase to buy goods, rather than using
cash. Motor finance figures were particularly strong, showing a 45 per cent
rise between December 1992 and last December.
The FLA said companies were starting to upgrade their car fleets, having
postponed such expenditure during the recession. Mr Tony Mallin, FLA
chairman, said April's tax rises would stretch consumers' cashflow and the
growth of retail sales would slow down.
Official figures for December consumer credit - which, unlike the FLA
figures, include bank credit cards - will be published on Monday.
Business finance figures were less strong, increasing by 13 per cent between
December 1992 and December 1993.
Mr Mallin said: 'We would expect the improvement in industrial investment to
lag behind consumer credit as we come out of recession, and our figures
reflect this. All the indications are that companies are now beginning to
invest in new plant and machinery.'
</TEXT>
