<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 94 / Rise in official reserves prompts sales speculation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The UK's official reserves rose by Dollars 521m in January, or by Dollars
205m on an underlying basis.
The larger-than-expected increase prompted some speculation in the markets
that the Bank of England had been selling pounds in order to counter the
strength of sterling.
However, intervention on such a small scale would have had little effect on
the pound's value, given that much larger sales of foreign currency failed
to prevent sterling's devaluation in September 1992.
The overall level of reserves at end-January was Dollars 43,447m, or Pounds
28,983m at the January 31 exchange rate. The underlying change excludes
factors such as dealings with the European Monetary Co-operation Fund, which
accounted for Dollars 298m of the rise.
The government continued to repay the revolving credit facility it took out
to help defend the pound when sterling was in the European exchange rate
mechanism. Just under Pounds 1.17bn of the facility was repaid in January.
</TEXT>
