<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 94 / A nation of highly profitable shopkeepers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GUY DE JONQUIERES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British retailers appear more vulnerable than many European counterparts to
the growth of cross-border competition in the industry and may be less
well-placed to expand into continental markets, says a study by the Oxford
Institute of Retail Management, Guy de Jonquieres writes.
The Europe-wide survey of retailers' financial performance finds that though
British retailers generate exceptionally high sales and profits from their
shelf space - most carry fewer days' stock than continental counterparts -
they are much less efficient in their use of assets and labour.
The institute suggests that UK retailers' high profits may mask inefficient
personnel management. In a comparison of sales per employee in 1992-93 among
almost 50 European retailers, Kwik Save, the best-performing British group,
ranks tenth and Marks &amp; Spencer twelfth, while 11 of the 15 chains at the
bottom of the list are British.
'One possible conclusion is that UK profit margins are good, but the ability
of UK retailers to work their assets is well below that displayed by other
European companies,' the study says. 'Questions might be posed as to how
well equipped UK companies are to meet fierce margin competition.'
The three worst performers, Boots, Burton and Sears, have sales per employee
roughly one-eighth those of Kesko of Finland, the highest-ranked European
retailer.
Seven of the 10 European companies generating the highest profits and sales
per square metre of store space are British. However, the study says UK
retailers may have less growth potential than their continental competitors
because of the difficulty in earning profits elsewhere in Europe that
compare with those in their home market.
European Retail Digest, Winter 1994. Oxford Institute of Retail Management,
Templeton College, Oxford. By subscription, Pounds 95 to commercial
enterprises, Pounds 80 to academic bodies.
